			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="65">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Every issue of <em>The Sun</em> brings nuggets of pure enjoyment. Sometimes it&rsquo;s the story, sometimes it&rsquo;s the writing, and sometimes it&rsquo;s both. Heather Sellers&rsquo;s frightening and astonishingly good essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/5020">I&rsquo;ll Never Bother You Again</a>&rdquo; [February 2015] was that rare combination.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Carol Myers<br>Chicago, Illinois</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="66">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Heather Sellers&rsquo;s memoir of being stalked has the suspense of a Hitchcock film and the emotionally abstracted viewpoint of a survivor. Her powers of observation make for a dramatic read.</p>

<p>During her kidnapping ordeal, Sellers shows us how she convinced her would-be murderer/rapist to return her home. Yet, when considering the memory, she says, &ldquo;I hadn&rsquo;t discovered a bold, brave part of myself.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;. I&rsquo;d discovered .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. that I could pretend to be someone I was not, and that people could be fooled by this, and that this could save my life.&rdquo;</p>

<p>What? It seems to me that she understood her kidnapper and became the person she needed to be to save her life. If that&rsquo;s not brave, I don&rsquo;t know what is.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Kip Leitner<br>Philadelphia, Pennsylvania</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

